TY  - JOUR
T1  - Hybrid and Size-Corrected Subsampling Methods
AU  - Andrews, Donald W. K.
AU  - Guggenberger, Patrik
Y1  - 2009/05/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA7015
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 721
EP  - 762
VL  - 77
IS  - 3
KW  - Asymptotic size
KW  - autoregressive model
KW  - m out of n bootstrap
KW  - exact size
KW  - hybrid test
KW  - model selection
KW  - over-rejection
KW  - size-correction
KW  - subsample
KW  - confidence interval
KW  - subsampling test
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA7015
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper considers inference in a broad class of nonregular models. The models considered are nonregular in the sense that standard test statistics have asymptotic distributions that are discontinuous in some parameters. It is shown in Andrews and Guggenberger (2009a) that standard fixed critical value, subsampling, and m out of n bootstrap methods often have incorrect asymptotic size in such models. This paper introduces general methods of constructing tests and confidence intervals that have correct asymptotic size. In particular, we consider a hybrid subsampling/fixed-critical-value method and size-correction methods. The paper discusses two examples in detail. They are (i) confidence intervals in an autoregressive model with a root that may be close to unity and conditional heteroskedasticity of unknown form and (ii) tests and confidence intervals based on a post-conservative model selection estimator.
ER  - 

